Meeting Qualification Standards
The foundation of successful pay-per-appointment relationships is rigorous, agreed-upon meeting qualification standards. Disputes about qualification represent the most common source of friction in these relationships.

Clear prospect profile criteria establish foundational qualification requirements. Organizations and providers should align explicitly on company size, industry, geography, and role definitions that qualify for compensation. Documenting these criteria in writing prevents misunderstandings.

Engagement quality standards define what constitutes a genuine meeting versus administrative checkbox completion. Quality standards should address meeting duration, prospect preparation, decision-maker participation, and demonstrated buying signal presence. Meetings where prospects attend but show minimal interest should not qualify for full compensation.

Timeline and continuity requirements ensure that appointments represent genuine business development opportunities. Minimum preparation time between contact and meeting ensures prospects aren't surprised. Continuity standards prevent vendors from booking consecutive meetings with same prospects in short timeframes, which would inflate appointment counts without advancing genuine sales conversations.

Decision-maker verification confirms that scheduled attendees possess relevant authority or influence. Roles should be documented. For high-value opportunities, organizations might require explicit verification that attendees have relevant authority before meetings qualify for payment.

Intent signal requirements verify that scheduled prospects show genuine buying intent rather than passive curiosity. Standards might require that prospects have engaged with relevant content, requested information, or indicated specific buying timelines before meetings qualify.

Documentation and proof requirements ensure that meetings actually occurred. Calendar invitations, attendance verification, meeting notes, or recordings provide evidence that scheduled meetings actually happened and met quality criteria.

